revision.text:
The '''1925 Indian riots''' refers to the sixteen communal riots which occurred throughout [[British India]]. Reported as being among the worst were in March in [[Delhi]], during September in [[Aligarh, Uttar Pradesh|Aligarh]], at [[Arvi, Wardha|Arvi]] in the [[Wardha district]] and in [[Solapur]].{{sfn|Simon|1930|p=100}}

== Aligarh ==
The Aligarh riot occurred on 22 September in the [[United Provinces of British India]] (now [[Uttar Pradesh]]). Of the sixteen communal riots that occurred that year, it was counted as one of the most severe. The [[The Times|London Times]] wrote two stories on the riots.{{sfn|Brass|2005|p=70}} The riot, was confined to Aligarh{{sfn|Bapu|2012|p=173}} which is in the top five of most riot prone cities in India.{{sfn|Gayer|2012|p=136}} According to a report from the [[Singapore Free Press]], on 24 September 1925, it had been said the rioting was caused by [[Mohammedan]] throwing stones at some Hindus during the festival of [[Ramlila]], the Hindus retaliated and in the ensuing violence sixty Muslim men and women were injured and twelve Hindus were hospitalized.{{sfn|Free Press|1925}}

[[Sheikh Abdullah]] speaking at a [[Indian Union Muslim League|Muslim League]] conference at Aligarh likened the year-long violence to the [[Crusades]], arguing that the most serious danger that Muslims had ever had to deal with was the current Hindu resurgence.{{sfn|Cell|2002|p=135}} The official number of those killed in the riot was six, four Muslims and two Hindus.{{sfn|Gayer|2012|p=136}}{{sfn|Brass|2005|p=71}}

