{{italic title}}
{{expand language|topic=|langcode=pt|otherarticle=Casa-Grande & Senzala|date=January 2014}}
Published in 1933, '''''Casa-Grande e Senzala''''' ({{lang-en|The Masters and the Slaves}}) is a book by [[Gilberto Freyre]], about the formation of [[Brazil]]ian society. The ''[[Casa grande (sugar plantation)|casa-grande]]'' ("big house") refers to the slave owner's residence on a [[sugarcane]] [[Sugar plantations in the Caribbean|plantation]], where whole towns were owned and managed by one man. The ''senzala'' ("[[slave quarters]]") refers to the dwellings of the black working class, where they originally worked as slaves, and later as servants.<ref name=musejhu>{{cite web|last=Barickman|first=B. J.|title=Revisiting the Casa-grande: Plantation and Cane-Farming Households in Early Nineteenth-Century Bahia|url=http://muse.jhu.edu/journals/hahr/summary/v084/84.4barickman.html|publisher=muse.jhu.edu|accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=jstor>{{cite web|title=The Masters and the Slaves [Casa-Grande &amp; Senzala]: A Study ...|url=https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/2507653?uid=16951160&uid=3738752&uid=2&uid=16821840&uid=3&uid=67&uid=363776971&uid=62&sid=21103326778311|publisher=jstor.org|accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=h-net>{{cite web|last=Veracini|first=Lorenzo|title=A. Isfahani-Hammond: White Negritude|url=http://www.h-net.org/reviews/showrev.php?id=29725|publisher=h-net.org|accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=ebscohost>{{cite web|last=Lehmann|first=David|title=GILBERTO FREYRE|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/literary-criticism/31209882/gilberto-freyre|publisher=connection.ebscohost.com|accessdate=31 January 2014}}</ref>

The book deals with race/class separation and [[miscegenation]] and is generally considered a classic of modern cultural anthropology. In [[Gilberto Freyre|Freyre's]] opinion, the hierarchy imposed by those in the Casa-Grande was an expression of a [[patriarchy|patriarchal]] society. In this book the author refutes the idea that Brazilians were an "inferior race" because of race-mixing. He points to the positive elements that permeated Brazilian culture because of miscegenation (especially among the Portuguese, Indians, and Africans). Portugal,  like Brazil, is described as being culturally and racially influenced by "an energetic infusion of Moorish and Negro blood, the effects of which persist to this day in the Portuguese people and the Portuguese character".<ref>Juan E. De Castro, ''Mestizo Nations: Culture, Race, and Conformity in Latin American Literature'', University of Arizona Press, 2002, p.68</ref><ref>Gilberto Freyre, ''Casa-grande E Senzala'', 1933, p. 211</ref>

