| Non-practising || Irregular || 2.3 || 37.8 || 59.9
|-
| Non-practising || Non-practising || 4.6 || 14.7 || 80.7
|}

A non-practicing mother with a regular father will see a minimum of two-thirds of her children ending up at church. In contrast, a non-practicing father with a regular mother will see two-thirds of his children not attending church. If his wife is similarly irregular that figure rises to 80 percent.<ref>{{cite journal | title = The Truth About Men & Church | journal = Touchstone | date = June 2003 | first = Robbie | last = Low | volume = 16 | issue = 5| id=| url = http://www.touchstonemag.com/archives/article.php?id=16-05-024-v |publisher= The Fellowship of St. James| accessdate = 2013-12-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Egan |first=Richard |url=http://www.ad2000.com.au/church_attendance_the_family_feminism_and_the_declining_role_of_fatherhood_september_2002 |title=Church Attendance: The family, feminism and the declining role of fatherhood |journal=AD2000 |volume=15 |issue=8 |date=September 2002 }}</ref>

An American study found similar results on the impact of fathers:<ref name="BruceBruce1996">{{cite book|last1=Bruce|first1=Robert|last2=Bruce|first2=Debra Fulghum|title=Becoming Spiritual Soulmates With Your Child|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y90JAAAACAAJ|year=1996|publisher=Broadman & Holman Publishers |location=Nashville |isbn=978-0-8054-6269-2|page=52}}</ref>
*When both parents attend [[Sunday school]], 72% of the children attend Sunday school when grown.
*When only the father attends Sunday school, 55% of the children attend when grown.
*When only the mother attends Sunday school, 15% of the children attend when grown.
*When neither parent attends Sunday school, only 6% of the children attend when grown.

An unrelated survey in the USA also found fathers to be highly influential in church attendance. It found that if a child is the first person in a household to become a Christian, there is a 3.5% probability everyone else in the household will follow. If the mother is the first to become a Christian, there is a 17% probability everyone else in the household will follow. However, when the father is first, there is a 93% probability everyone else in the household will follow.<ref name="HornerRalston1996">{{cite book|author1=Bob Horner|author2=Ron Ralston|author3=David Sunde|title=The promise keeper at work|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CglElq-WtecC|accessdate=12 November 2013|series=Promise Builders Study Series|date=December 1996|publisher=Focus on the Family Publishing|isbn=978-1-56179-451-5|page=111}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.bpnews.net/bpnews.asp?id=15630 | title = Baptist Press: Want your church to grow? Then bring in the men | accessdate = 2013-11-12 | last = House | first = Polly | date = 2003-04-03 | publisher = Baptist Press}}</ref>

== Trends ==
[[File:Ashes_to_Go_at_Palmer_Memorial_Episcopal_Church.jpg|thumb|250px|The Christian season of Lent begins on [[Ash Wednesday]], most notably by the public imposition of ashes. In this photograph, a woman receives a cross of ashes on Ash Wednesday at an [[Anglican]] Christian church.]]
Church attendance in advanced industrial societies is in gradual general decline with people shifting from weekly to monthly or holiday attendance. Sociologists have attributed this trend to a number of reasons, starting from a simple boredom during services and lack of motivation, to generational incompatibility of belief systems and social changes attributed to modernity.<ref name="Christian Research Association">[https://web.archive.org/web/20100801010204/http://www.cra.org.au/pages/00000242.cgi Why People Don't Go to Church... ]. Accessed through Internet Archives on 19 January 2014.</ref> Research across 65 different nations showed that out of 20 advanced industrial countries - 16 demonstrated a declining rate of monthly church attendance.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Inglehart | first1 = Ronald | last2 = Baker | first2 = Wayne E. | year = 2000 | title = Modernization, Cultural Change, and the Persistence of Traditional Values | url = http://my.fit.edu/~gabrenya/cultural/readings/Inglehart-Baker-2000.pdf | format = PDF | journal = American Sociological Review | volume = 65 | issue = | pages = 19–51 | doi=10.2307/2657288}}</ref>

An article published in the ''Christianity Today Magazine'' emphasized that at least in America church attendance since the 1990s has remained stable.<ref>Hunter Baker. [http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2007/novemberweb-only/145-42.0.html Is Church Attendance Declining?], 11 August 2007.</ref> Indeed, 50% of Americans replied that God is very important in their lives, comparing with 40% of Irish, 28% of Canadians, 26% of Spaniards, 21% of Australians, and 10% of the French.<ref>Dillon, Michele. [https://books.google.com/books?id=BFWlhQRhQ6gC&pg=PA85&dq=Church+attendance&hl=en&sa=X&ei=vmXcUpOHKvK_sQTOj4H4Cg&ved=0CDMQ6AEwATgK#v=onepage&q=Church%20attendance&f=false Handbook of the Sociology of Religion]. Cambridge, U.K.: Cambridge University Press, 2003, p. 90.</ref>

The percent of Americans who regularly attend religious services has fluctuated over time, but presently is at a low point.<ref name="Newport">Frank Newport, [http://www.gallup.com/poll/200186/five-key-findings-religion.aspx Five Key Findings on Religion in the US], Gallup Poll (December 23, 2017).</ref> In [[Gallup Poll]] surveys, the yearly aggregate of those who answer "yes" to the question "Did you, yourself, happen to attend church or synagogue in the last seven days, or not?" was 36% in 2014, 2015, and 2016.<ref name="GallupPoll">[http://www.gallup.com/poll/1690/religion.aspx Religion], Gallup Poll (last accessed May 12, 2017).</ref> This is a very long-running Gallup question: "In 1939, when Gallup first asked this question, 41% said 'yes.' That percentage dropped to 37% in 1940 and rose to 39% in 1950. It continued to climb, reaching as high as 49% at multiple points in the 1950s. Attendance then settled down to figures around 40% for decades, before dropping to 36%" beginning in 2014.<ref name="Newport"/>

The decline in church attendance is more pronounced in developed European countries, where it is suggested that the secular culture overrides interest in religion. In Poland Church attendance has declined from more than 50% in 1979 to 40% in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Praktyki niedzielne Polaków (dominicantes)|url = http://iskk.pl/kosciolnaswiecie/211-praktyki-niedzielne-polakow-dominicantes.html|website = iskk.pl|accessdate = 2015-12-21}}</ref>

== Criticism ==
In the early 1990s, American sociologists Kirk Hadaway, Penny Marler, and Mark Chaves found that weekly attendance at Protestant and Catholic churches in one rural county in [[Ohio]] was only about 20%, whereas self-reported church attendance was 36%.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hadaway |first1=C. Kirk |last2=Marler |first2=Penny Long |last3=Chaves |first3=Mark |url=http://www.stat.columbia.edu/~gelman/stuff_for_blog/church0.pdf |title=What the polls don't show: A closer look at U.S. church attendance |journal=American Sociological Review |date=December 1993 |volume=58 |issue=6 |pages=741–52 |jstor=2095948 |doi=10.2307/2095948 }}</ref> The following studies confirmed a long-suspected gap between actual and self-reporting church attendance.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hadaway |first1=C. Kirk |first2=Penny Long |last2=Marler |url=http://www.religion-online.org/showarticle.asp?|title=Did You Really Go To Church This Week? Behind the Poll Data |journal=The Christian Century |date=May 6, 1998 |volume=115 |issue=14 |pages=472–5 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hadaway |first1=C. Kirk |last2=Marler |first2=Penny Long |last3=Chaves |first3=Mark |url=http://www.stat.columbia.edu/~gelman/stuff_for_blog/church4.pdf |title=Overreporting church attendance in America: Evidence that demands the same verdict |journal=American Sociological Review |date=February 1998 |volume=63 |issue=1 |pages=122–30 |jstor=2657484 | doi=10.2307/2657484 }}</ref> The researchers have been wary of accusing over-reporters of dishonesty, as they found in the study that those who over-report do so mainly to maintain perceptions of themselves as "churched" Americans, not because they are afraid to reveal to the interviewer that they are "bad Christians."<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.2307/3711747 |jstor=3711747 |title=Testing the Attendance Gap in a Conservative Church |journal=Sociology of Religion |volume=60 |issue=2 |pages=175–86 |year=1999 |last1=Marler |first1=Penny Long |last2=Hadaway |first2=C. Kirk }}</ref> The findings point to a bigger issue as many people in the world may be over-reporting church attendance because of their self-perception and identity as churchgoing people, indicating a certain psychological aspect to the over-reporting of church attendance. Although surveys of church attendance are aimed to study religious behavior, many respondents view them as questions about their identity. This is especially true among Americans who consider themselves "regular churchgoers."<ref>[http://hirr.hartsem.edu/about/news_and_notes_vol4no1.html The Church Attendance Gap: A look at two older studies whose findings should be taken more seriously] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131130031340/http://hirr.hartsem.edu/about/news_and_notes_vol4no1.html |date=2013-11-30 }}. ''Hartford Institutes for Religious Research News and Notes'', Vol. IV, No. 1.</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080516014545/http://religions.pewforum.org/reports Pew Research: Religious Landscape Survey].{{dead link|date=December 2016}}{{full citation needed|date=December 2016}}</ref>

